00:31:53.440 --> 00:31:53.640
If

532
00:31:54.660 --> 00:31:56.800
there are no more questions, thank you so much.

533
00:31:56.860 --> 00:31:57.380
Thank you very much.

534
00:32:00.720 --> 00:32:04.200
Our next speaker will be Shuyang He from

535
00:32:04.800 --> 00:32:08.700
WashU, St. Louis, and she will talk about stress remodeling

536
00:32:08.760 --> 00:32:11.780
of enteric neural system

537
00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:15.700
in colitis to cancer transition.

538
00:32:16.580 --> 00:32:20.140
All right. Thank you for the introduction. Is the sound okay?

539
00:32:20.880 --> 00:32:21.300
All right.

540
00:32:22.260 --> 00:32:26.160
So cancer patients are undergoing all different kind of stresses

541
00:32:26.200 --> 00:32:30.080
from being diagnosed to all through all these treatments, and also

542
00:32:30.140 --> 00:32:30.880
worry about the

543
00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:35.400
collapse. So it is of note that one-third of the cancer

544
00:32:35.480 --> 00:32:39.340
patients will develop a mental health problem, and half of

545
00:32:39.380 --> 00:32:41.960
them will experience anxiety or depression.

546
00:32:43.140 --> 00:32:46.890
From large scale of epidemiological studies, we know that

547
00:32:46.890 --> 00:32:50.640
stress-related psychosocial factors associated with

548
00:32:50.760 --> 00:32:54.340
higher incidence and poorer survival in cancer patients.

549
00:32:54.420 --> 00:32:58.260
Social support, on the other hand, which can release the stress from the

550
00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:02.020
cancer patients, has been proved with longer survival in these

551
00:33:02.120 --> 00:33:05.960
patients. So as a systemic effect, it means

552
00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:08.280
that stress can affect our whole body.

553
00:33:08.760 --> 00:33:12.300
So my lab is of particularly interested in the gut system now.

554
00:33:12.780 --> 00:33:16.620
So it is not only because the gut is closely related to our daily

555
00:33:16.640 --> 00:33:20.540
life, but also because colorectal cancer is ranking number three in

556
00:33:20.580 --> 00:33:24.160
the United States, meaning a lot of people are stressed out about this.

557
00:33:24.980 --> 00:33:28.640
So although there are many evidence showing that genetic mutations like

558
00:33:28.700 --> 00:33:32.060
KRAS or APC are driving the colorectal cancer onset,

559
00:33:32.589 --> 00:33:35.760
there are more and more studies showing that these bad

560
00:33:36.320 --> 00:33:40.160
lifestyle factors are also associated with the early

561
00:33:40.180 --> 00:33:43.480
onset of colorectal cancer, including mental stress.

562
00:33:44.630 --> 00:33:48.380
So to further understand the relationship between stress and the colorectal

563
00:33:48.420 --> 00:33:52.400
cancer onset, we first looked into the published database

564
00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:56.470
from the UK Biobank, which has a huge amount of population

565
00:33:56.540 --> 00:34:00.430
data. For example, as shown here, when comparing

566
00:34:00.500 --> 00:34:04.280
these patients with psychiatric disorders, the risk of them

567
00:34:04.300 --> 00:34:07.100
getting colorectal cancer is much higher.

568
00:34:08.060 --> 00:34:11.700
Moreover, when grouping these patients into different

569
00:34:11.720 --> 00:34:15.520
disorders like depression or anxiety or psychological

570
00:34:15.580 --> 00:34:19.380
stress, the risk factors for them for the CRC

571
00:34:19.400 --> 00:34:22.281
incidence is also higher than the healthy controls.

572
00:34:23.740 --> 00:34:27.400
So to further understand how stress promotes the colorectal cancer

573
00:34:27.460 --> 00:34:30.620
onset, we went back to the mouse models in the lab.

574
00:34:31.540 --> 00:34:35.100
From the past several years, we and others have used

575
00:34:35.281 --> 00:34:38.660
different mouse models to study how stress promotes cancer

576
00:34:38.761 --> 00:34:42.680
progression. And we have identified that stress by

577
00:34:42.761 --> 00:34:46.440
activation of the HPA axis through the release of the stress

578
00:34:46.480 --> 00:34:50.460
hormone like glucocorticoids, where stress can activate the sympathetic

579
00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:52.920
nervous system in the mice.

580
00:34:54.040 --> 00:34:58.020
So to really mimic the stress response in the mouse, we're now using

581
00:34:58.080 --> 00:35:00.960
a physical restraint model to mimic stress.

582
00:35:01.020 --> 00:35:04.680
So as shown here, the physical restraint model can lead to much higher

583
00:35:04.740 --> 00:35:08.660
levels of corticosterone, which means that these mice are under

584
00:35:08.700 --> 00:35:09.100
stress.

585
00:35:10.100 --> 00:35:13.900
So with this model being established, we next combine it with the

586
00:35:13.920 --> 00:35:17.660
colorectal cancer model. So we first started with the Apc min

587
00:35:17.720 --> 00:35:21.220
mouse model, in which all the mice carry a loss-of-function

588
00:35:21.280 --> 00:35:25.140
mutation of the Apc gene, and this is also the first step for

589
00:35:25.200 --> 00:35:28.100
CRC onset in most of the cancer patients.

590
00:35:29.380 --> 00:35:33.190
As you can see here within this model, delayed physical restraint

591
00:35:33.260 --> 00:35:37.070
stress can significantly promote tumor genesis, and these

592
00:35:37.100 --> 00:35:40.100
mice have developed more numbers of the tumors.

593
00:35:40.150 --> 00:35:44.080
So this indicates that under the same genetic background, being

594
00:35:44.180 --> 00:35:46.760
stressed can promote the tumor initiation.

595
00:35:48.160 --> 00:35:51.940
So this phenomenon was not only limited in this Apc min mouse model,

596
00:35:52.260 --> 00:35:55.860
but can also be found in multiple mouse models, including the

597
00:35:55.920 --> 00:35:58.700
inducible CRC model and the spontaneous model.

598
00:35:59.480 --> 00:36:03.360
So in both cases, we have shown that daily stress can promote

599
00:36:03.440 --> 00:36:04.180
more numbers

600
00:36:05.380 --> 00:36:09.100
of the tumor happening throughout the gut, meaning that the stress can

601
00:36:09.140 --> 00:36:11.020
really promote the cancer onset.

602
00:36:12.380 --> 00:36:15.600
So before getting into any mechanistic studies, I

603
00:36:15.640 --> 00:36:19.180
would like to highlight here that gut is a highly

604
00:36:19.240 --> 00:36:23.180
innervated organ. So here I'm showing you a 3D whole mount

605
00:36:23.240 --> 00:36:24.960
imaging from this cleared tissue.

606
00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:29.240
You can see here the gut has extensive blood vessels, which are

607
00:36:29.340 --> 00:36:31.900
mediating the nutrient absorption.

608
00:36:32.480 --> 00:36:35.640
But around these blood vessels here is enteric nervous

609
00:36:35.720 --> 00:36:39.340
system. It includes the enteric glia cells labeled in

610
00:36:39.460 --> 00:36:43.204
red and the nerves stained in white.So these two

611
00:36:43.304 --> 00:36:47.064
types of the cells, the nerves plus the glia cells, has made

612
00:36:47.184 --> 00:36:50.744
this neuronal network within the gut, and they are

613
00:36:50.784 --> 00:36:54.344
playing critical roles in maintaining the gut homeostasis.

614
00:36:56.244 --> 00:37:00.004
So within this nervous system, we are focusing now on

615
00:37:00.084 --> 00:37:03.884
the role of glia cells, given its known role during the

616
00:37:03.924 --> 00:37:07.684
CRC development. So we first generated a gene

617
00:37:07.784 --> 00:37:11.724
signature expressed exclusively by the enteric glia cells,

618
00:37:11.824 --> 00:37:15.784
or the EGCs. When we applied this gene signature into the

619
00:37:15.824 --> 00:37:19.224
TCGA database for CRC patients, I hope you can

620
00:37:19.264 --> 00:37:22.524
appreciate that the patients who had the higher

621
00:37:22.784 --> 00:37:26.504
expression of this gene signature, meaning that their tumors

622
00:37:26.664 --> 00:37:30.624
probably are more infiltrated by glia cells, they actually had much

623
00:37:30.664 --> 00:37:31.844
shorter survival time.

624
00:37:33.264 --> 00:37:37.044
So to further understand or characterize the roles of

625
00:37:37.084 --> 00:37:40.954
EGCs during the CRC development, we next compared

626
00:37:40.964 --> 00:37:44.144
the EGC infiltration across different stages

627
00:37:44.884 --> 00:37:48.704
during the CRC development. However, to our surprise,

628
00:37:48.824 --> 00:37:52.664
we found that there are a lot of glia cells infiltrated into

629
00:37:52.684 --> 00:37:56.484
the polyps or the benign tumors at the initial stage.

630
00:37:56.544 --> 00:38:00.104
As you can see here, the glia cells are labeled in green with

631
00:38:00.404 --> 00:38:04.204
as 100 beta staining, and they're hanging around the cancer cells in

632
00:38:04.264 --> 00:38:04.464
red.

633
00:38:05.364 --> 00:38:09.264
However, when the tumors grow larger or become more advanced, we could

634
00:38:09.284 --> 00:38:11.324
barely find any glia cells inside.

635
00:38:12.444 --> 00:38:16.384
So this data has prompted us to think about the role of EGC in the

636
00:38:16.444 --> 00:38:19.714
initial stage. So we next decided to deplete them.

637
00:38:20.724 --> 00:38:23.224
We took advantage of a mouse strain called

638
00:38:23.324 --> 00:38:27.314
Plp1creERT RosatTTR mice, in which we could

639
00:38:27.444 --> 00:38:31.094
specifically deplete the glia cells in the gut following

640
00:38:31.204 --> 00:38:34.564
the injection of tamoxifen and diphtheria toxin.

641
00:38:35.964 --> 00:38:39.704
So, as confirmed here, we show that the glia cells can be

642
00:38:39.744 --> 00:38:42.564
largely depleted in the gut. So we then

643
00:38:43.424 --> 00:38:47.214
back cross this mouse strain within the ApcMin background

644
00:38:47.564 --> 00:38:51.364
and subjected all these mice into this stress-induced CRC model.

645
00:38:52.484 --> 00:38:56.364
So I think the data is pretty striking by just looking at this picture.

646
00:38:56.724 --> 00:38:58.464
So simply by depleting the

647
00:38:59.284 --> 00:39:02.844
glia cells at the very early stage could significantly

648
00:39:02.864 --> 00:39:05.204
reduce stress-induced tumorigenesis.

649
00:39:06.544 --> 00:39:10.364
So after identifying that the glia cells are in the tumor

650
00:39:10.444 --> 00:39:14.084
microenvironment to promote tumor initiation, we were

651
00:39:14.164 --> 00:39:17.324
then wondering, how do these glia cells promote

652
00:39:17.604 --> 00:39:19.784
tumorigenesis? So we then turn

653
00:39:20.944 --> 00:39:23.164
back to our in vitro culturing system.

654
00:39:23.884 --> 00:39:27.844
So we generated the organoid line from this ApcMin mice.

655
00:39:28.124 --> 00:39:30.404
We call it as a pre-tumor organoid lines.

656
00:39:30.984 --> 00:39:34.824
And at the same time, we also collected the conditioned medium from the

657
00:39:34.884 --> 00:39:38.844
stressed glia cells, meaning that we pre-treated the cells with the

658
00:39:38.864 --> 00:39:41.724
glucocorticoid or the GR receptor

659
00:39:42.524 --> 00:39:43.024
agonist.

660
00:39:44.124 --> 00:39:47.914
So what we found is that when treating this pre-cancer organoid with the

661
00:39:47.964 --> 00:39:51.744
conditioned medium from stressed glia cells, can significantly

662
00:39:51.784 --> 00:39:54.204
promote the outgrowth of these organoids.

663
00:39:55.184 --> 00:39:59.144
So to better understand at the molecular level, how do these glia

664
00:39:59.204 --> 00:40:03.184
cells promote tumorigenesis, we next perform the qPCR on

665
00:40:03.204 --> 00:40:07.134
this pre-cancer organoid. As you can appreciate here, all these

666
00:40:07.184 --> 00:40:10.484
tumorigenesis-related genes have been all

667
00:40:10.564 --> 00:40:14.334
upregulated when treating these organoids with the conditioned

668
00:40:14.344 --> 00:40:16.664
medium from stressed EGCs.

669
00:40:17.914 --> 00:40:21.394
So to further understand any clinical relevance of our study,

670
00:40:21.884 --> 00:40:24.884
we next compared the cross-species of our data.

671
00:40:25.364 --> 00:40:29.204
As you can see here, what we have found for these transcriptional changes

672
00:40:29.564 --> 00:40:33.284
in the mouse organoid can be very well recapitulated with a

673
00:40:33.324 --> 00:40:34.224
human database.

674
00:40:35.564 --> 00:40:39.164
So after knowing that the EGCs are in the microenvironment

675
00:40:39.324 --> 00:40:43.294
playing some role in promoting tumorigenesis, we next are wondering,

676
00:40:43.764 --> 00:40:46.344
is there any cell intrinsic response to stress?

677
00:40:46.984 --> 00:40:50.644
So to study this, we look at the early time point in our model.

678
00:40:51.884 --> 00:40:55.624
So getting inspired by previous studies showing that stress can

679
00:40:55.684 --> 00:40:59.604
induce reactive oxygen species, or ROS, in the gut, we

680
00:40:59.663 --> 00:41:02.764
next examined this oxidative damage within our

681
00:41:02.804 --> 00:41:05.124
system. As you can see here, with

682
00:41:05.984 --> 00:41:09.764
two different marker staining, we show that the gut tissue from the

683
00:41:09.844 --> 00:41:13.824
stressed mice do have elevated ROS, indicating that they

684
00:41:13.844 --> 00:41:16.164
are undergoing oxidative damage.

685
00:41:17.224 --> 00:41:21.004
So consequently of this oxidative damage, we

686
00:41:21.024 --> 00:41:24.844
also found that the gut cells from the stressed mice do show more

687
00:41:24.884 --> 00:41:27.984
DNA double-strand damage, as indicated by

688
00:41:28.024 --> 00:41:29.504
gamma-H2AX staining.

689
00:41:30.604 --> 00:41:34.484
But it's very interestingly that, although under all different kinds

690
00:41:34.584 --> 00:41:37.124
of damage, these gut cells from the stressed

691
00:41:38.264 --> 00:41:40.404
mice are also hyperproliferating.

692
00:41:40.824 --> 00:41:44.524
So here, as indicated by the Ki-67 staining, these

693
00:41:44.664 --> 00:41:48.504
abnormal damaged cells are hyperproliferating, and maybe

694
00:41:48.564 --> 00:41:51.664
this is the reason that they will undergo tumorigenesis.

695
00:41:53.104 --> 00:41:56.604
So in summary, our data has generated

696
00:41:57.004 --> 00:42:00.744
a stressed EGC-stem cell axis, and by activating

697
00:42:00.804 --> 00:42:02.664
this axis can trigger the tumor

698
00:42:03.544 --> 00:42:07.284
initiation in the mice. Magnetically, we found that

699
00:42:07.864 --> 00:42:11.644
the stressed glia cells, meaning that the activation of the GR

700
00:42:11.704 --> 00:42:15.164
pathways in these glia cells, are the driver in the gut

701
00:42:15.224 --> 00:42:19.044
microenvironment to trigger all these transcriptional changes in the

702
00:42:19.224 --> 00:42:22.384
stem cells, and finally becoming a tumor cell.

703
00:42:24.164 --> 00:42:28.004
So within this project, we also have some open questions

704
00:42:28.124 --> 00:42:31.924
for the future direction. First, the glia cells are really

705
00:42:31.944 --> 00:42:35.604
heterogeneous. So from recently published single-cell

706
00:42:35.684 --> 00:42:39.554
data, we know that there are at least four types of glia cells

707
00:42:39.564 --> 00:42:43.084
throughout the gut. So what we don't know is that if there is any

708
00:42:43.164 --> 00:42:47.004
location-specific or subtype-specific response

709
00:42:47.104 --> 00:42:50.424
to stress of these glia cells, and how this can be involved in

710
00:42:50.464 --> 00:42:54.434
cancer.So second, so for this project, we

711
00:42:54.454 --> 00:42:58.194
are working on understanding the glia's crosstalk with the stem

712
00:42:58.294 --> 00:43:01.774
cells, but they're also surrounded with other cell types.

713
00:43:01.904 --> 00:43:05.844
For example, whenever we did the staining for the glia cells, they always

714
00:43:05.874 --> 00:43:09.774
come along with the nerve cells. So what we don't know is that under stress

715
00:43:09.854 --> 00:43:13.714
condition, if there's any change of the nerves and whether and how this can

716
00:43:13.794 --> 00:43:17.274
be involved during the stress-induced tumor genesis.

717
00:43:18.374 --> 00:43:21.914
So with that, I would like to thank my lab members, especially

718
00:43:21.954 --> 00:43:24.654
Xiaoxiao, she's here, she's a mom now, and Chenchen.

719
00:43:25.074 --> 00:43:29.054
They are contributing significantly to this project, and happy to take

720
00:43:29.114 --> 00:43:29.774
any questions.

721
00:43:34.674 --> 00:43:35.474
Questions, please.

722
00:43:37.134 --> 00:43:40.494
Quick question about can you simplify your model,

723
00:43:40.694 --> 00:43:43.934
stress or no stress, if you just inject cortisol?

724
00:43:44.674 --> 00:43:48.374
Will it produce all the effects on glia and

725
00:43:48.474 --> 00:43:52.034
then on colitis or spontaneous tumor genesis?

726
00:43:52.804 --> 00:43:56.294
This is a very good question. I think my trainees will be very happy to know

727
00:43:56.353 --> 00:43:57.353
because they have to come to

728
00:43:58.234 --> 00:44:01.994
lab every day to stress the mice. And I think the simple answer

729
00:44:02.054 --> 00:44:05.614
is yes, because we tried in a different model with breast

730
00:44:05.624 --> 00:44:09.454
cancer, in which we injected dexamethasone to mimic

731
00:44:09.514 --> 00:44:11.334
stress response, and we saw the same

732
00:44:12.554 --> 00:44:16.274
results for breast cancer liver metastasis, but we haven't tested in the

733
00:44:16.334 --> 00:44:16.634
gut.

734
00:44:18.374 --> 00:44:19.594
Okay.

735
00:44:19.634 --> 00:44:22.514
Yeah. Tim Wong from Columbia. Really nice talk.

736
00:44:23.464 --> 00:44:23.484
Thank you.

737
00:44:23.484 --> 00:44:27.294
I like that you used the restraint stress model, which is very reproducible.

738
00:44:28.094 --> 00:44:31.414
So you focus a lot on the HPA axis, and you focus more on the

739
00:44:31.514 --> 00:44:35.154
glucocorticoid response, but you really didn't mention the

740
00:44:35.194 --> 00:44:38.704
adrenergic response and the effects of epinephrine and norepinephrine,

741
00:44:39.214 --> 00:44:42.594
which go up under stress and maybe under cold conditions.

742
00:44:43.034 --> 00:44:46.654
So did you look at whether or not adrenergic

743
00:44:46.734 --> 00:44:50.684
signaling played a role? Did you look at ADRP2 signaling, for

744
00:44:50.714 --> 00:44:51.084
example?

745
00:44:51.804 --> 00:44:55.674
Yes, very good question. So in another independent

746
00:44:55.684 --> 00:44:59.634
project with breast cancer, we actually look at the sympathetic

747
00:44:59.644 --> 00:45:02.974
nerves. We found that activation of the nerves specifically

748
00:45:03.034 --> 00:45:06.913
locally in the breast can also promote tumor growth in the

749
00:45:06.934 --> 00:45:09.834
primary site. But in the gut, it's a little bit different.

750
00:45:10.134 --> 00:45:13.894
So we try to identify the nerve types within the gut,

751
00:45:14.154 --> 00:45:17.794
and we found in the colon, these sympathetic nerves are really

752
00:45:17.814 --> 00:45:20.174
located in the smooth muscle layer.

753
00:45:20.554 --> 00:45:24.094
So when we dissected other neuron types, we found it's mostly like

754
00:45:24.234 --> 00:45:27.894
VIP or vasoactive intestinal peptide, VIP

755
00:45:27.914 --> 00:45:31.634
positive nerves, and endos positive nerves in the gut and also in the

756
00:45:31.714 --> 00:45:34.494
tumor. So we guess probably it's not the

757
00:45:34.594 --> 00:45:38.494
sympathetic nerves directly

758
00:45:38.554 --> 00:45:41.334
working on, but it is also possible because

759
00:45:41.394 --> 00:45:44.834
it's innervated into the smooth muscle layer,

760
00:45:45.234 --> 00:45:49.174
which has a lot of ganglia. So there's a possibility that it

761
00:45:49.234 --> 00:45:53.114
talks to the ganglia of the nerves in the gut and then

762
00:45:53.254 --> 00:45:56.934
transmit the signal into the tumor, but we haven't looked at it.

763
00:45:56.994 --> 00:45:57.994
Great question. Thank you.

764
00:45:58.274 --> 00:45:58.554
Please.

765
00:46:00.174 --> 00:46:02.114
Thanks for your fascinating presentation.

766
00:46:02.264 --> 00:46:04.134
I just have a question about the gut microbiome.

767
00:46:05.774 --> 00:46:09.723
A lot of the bacteria that are associated with psychiatric disorders

768
00:46:10.534 --> 00:46:11.764
are also associated with

769
00:46:12.674 --> 00:46:14.054
colonic tumorigenesis.

770
00:46:15.074 --> 00:46:18.814
And I was wondering if you can close the loop,

771
00:46:18.854 --> 00:46:22.794
whether the glial cells impact the bacterial populations that are in

772
00:46:22.834 --> 00:46:23.254
the gut,

773
00:46:24.094 --> 00:46:27.774
or how do you think about the microbiome in light of your

774
00:46:27.814 --> 00:46:30.114
work from a sort of systems point of view?

775
00:46:30.704 --> 00:46:34.074
Great. I think this is a very good question.

776
00:46:34.114 --> 00:46:38.024
So we actually have a project ongoing in my lab in which we are looking at

777
00:46:38.134 --> 00:46:41.934
how stress affects the colitis. And we have some preliminary data of

