1673
01:35:47.660 --> 01:35:51.540
from Fred Hutch Cancer Center, and he will talk about

1674
01:35:51.620 --> 01:35:55.560
immunotherapy resistance to bone metastasis mediated

1675
01:35:55.660 --> 01:35:57.820
by myeloid-driven mechanisms.

1676
01:35:58.700 --> 01:36:02.440
I thank the organizers for this opportunity. My name is Aram Liu.

1677
01:36:02.460 --> 01:36:04.430
I'm a post-doctoral fellow under the mentorship of Dr.

1678
01:36:04.550 --> 01:36:06.660
Larry Fong at Fred Hutch Cancer Center.

1679
01:36:07.340 --> 01:36:11.300
Today, I'll be presenting how myeloid cell-mediated immunotherapy

1680
01:36:11.380 --> 01:36:15.020
resistance mechanisms evolve during prostate cancer progression,

1681
01:36:15.160 --> 01:36:17.600
particularly in bone metastasis.

1682
01:36:19.100 --> 01:36:20.300
I have nothing to disclose.

1683
01:36:21.800 --> 01:36:25.060
Prostate cancer is among the most common male malignancies.

1684
01:36:25.580 --> 01:36:28.960
Although immunotherapies, including immune checkpoint blockade, have

1685
01:36:29.060 --> 01:36:32.940
revolutionized cancer treatment, patients with advanced prostate

1686
01:36:32.980 --> 01:36:36.820
cancer remain largely unresponsive to these therapeutic

1687
01:36:36.880 --> 01:36:40.860
options. For example, patients treated with atezolizumab,

1688
01:36:40.960 --> 01:36:44.680
which is PD-L1 blockade, shown in blue, showed marginal

1689
01:36:44.760 --> 01:36:47.900
efficacy compared to those treated with control arms.

1690
01:36:49.460 --> 01:36:53.300
This therapeutic resistance is partly due

1691
01:36:53.340 --> 01:36:56.560
to the presence of immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment.

1692
01:36:57.040 --> 01:37:00.500
Particularly, tumor-associated myeloid cells are

1693
01:37:00.580 --> 01:37:03.380
encouraging and promising immunotherapeutic targets.

1694
01:37:04.220 --> 01:37:07.840
It's been well reported that immunosuppressive myeloid cells,

1695
01:37:07.960 --> 01:37:11.900
including macrophages on the left and another suppressing

1696
01:37:11.940 --> 01:37:15.820
myeloid population called myeloid-derived suppressor cells, become

1697
01:37:15.880 --> 01:37:19.040
significantly enriched during prostate cancer progression.

1698
01:37:19.880 --> 01:37:23.760
However, efforts to target these myeloid cells broadly, such as

1699
01:37:23.780 --> 01:37:27.720
with CSFR1 receptor blockade, showed minimal efficacy

1700
01:37:27.740 --> 01:37:28.580
in patients.

1701
01:37:29.720 --> 01:37:32.780
So our lab hypothesized that if we

1702
01:37:32.860 --> 01:37:35.790
identify distinct immunosuppressive myeloid

1703
01:37:35.860 --> 01:37:39.720
subpopulations that signals a resolution, we may be able to

1704
01:37:39.760 --> 01:37:41.500
enhance immunotherapy efficacy in

1705
01:37:41.620 --> 01:37:45.010
patients.To address this question,

1706
01:37:45.460 --> 01:37:48.860
we have previously investigated the primary tumor

1707
01:37:48.880 --> 01:37:52.740
biopsies across multiple stages and identified

1708
01:37:52.760 --> 01:37:56.360
a distinct macrophage population expressing elevated

1709
01:37:56.420 --> 01:37:59.920
levels of SPP1 transcript, which encodes the protein

1710
01:37:59.980 --> 01:38:00.800
osteopontin.

1711
01:38:02.000 --> 01:38:05.540
These macrophages become significantly enriched during disease

1712
01:38:05.620 --> 01:38:09.100
progression with enriched immunosuppressive molecular

1713
01:38:09.200 --> 01:38:09.800
programs.

1714
01:38:10.760 --> 01:38:14.580
Through preclinical studies, we demonstrated

1715
01:38:14.590 --> 01:38:18.560
that these macrophages drive immunotherapy resistance, shown

1716
01:38:18.600 --> 01:38:22.020
in blue versus red, via adenosine signaling

1717
01:38:22.080 --> 01:38:25.900
pathways. So these findings inform the clinical trial

1718
01:38:26.400 --> 01:38:29.620
showing that blockade of adenosine receptor

1719
01:38:30.120 --> 01:38:33.940
synergize with atezolizumab, shown in red, compared to

1720
01:38:33.980 --> 01:38:36.820
monotherapies. And these macrophage

1721
01:38:37.000 --> 01:38:40.860
population may serve as predictive biomarkers.

1722
01:38:42.300 --> 01:38:45.860
Although these longitudinal studies have provided

1723
01:38:46.020 --> 01:38:47.800
significant clinical insights,

1724
01:38:50.440 --> 01:38:54.080
these findings were primarily derived from primary

1725
01:38:54.100 --> 01:38:54.700
tumors.

1726
01:38:56.140 --> 01:38:59.660
And prostate cancer tend to spread to multiple organs,

1727
01:38:59.900 --> 01:39:03.260
including bone, liver, and lymph nodes.

1728
01:39:03.300 --> 01:39:06.860
And given majority of patients ultimately succumb to metastatic

1729
01:39:06.940 --> 01:39:10.860
disease, we hypothesize that if we characterize

1730
01:39:10.900 --> 01:39:14.500
myeloid departments across multiple metastatic organs,

1731
01:39:14.880 --> 01:39:18.660
we may be able to distinct these immunotherapeutic targets.

1732
01:39:20.120 --> 01:39:23.940
To address this question, we added more primary biopsies,

1733
01:39:24.200 --> 01:39:28.010
particularly from metastatic organs, to existing single

1734
01:39:28.100 --> 01:39:31.700
cell transcriptomes and conducted further transcriptional

1735
01:39:31.760 --> 01:39:32.520
analysis.

1736
01:39:34.360 --> 01:39:38.300
We found that a distinct organ has a unique

1737
01:39:39.180 --> 01:39:42.860
immune and non-immune environment, notably bone

1738
01:39:42.900 --> 01:39:46.340
metastasis, which is the most common organ of

1739
01:39:47.300 --> 01:39:50.720
prostate cancer spread, showed a unique tumor

1740
01:39:50.780 --> 01:39:54.559
microenvironment with neutrophils as a dominant component,

1741
01:39:54.619 --> 01:39:55.500
shown in green.

1742
01:39:57.280 --> 01:40:01.060
Importantly, we found that SPP1 high macrophages

1743
01:40:01.120 --> 01:40:05.020
that we reported showed a marginal scarcity

1744
01:40:05.600 --> 01:40:08.960
in bone metastasis compared to soft tissue sites,

1745
01:40:09.400 --> 01:40:13.020
highlighting the need for organ-specific investigations.

1746
01:40:13.920 --> 01:40:17.680
So we hypothesize that single cell characterization of myeloid

1747
01:40:17.740 --> 01:40:21.620
cells, particularly neutrophils in bone metastasis, may

1748
01:40:21.660 --> 01:40:23.520
reveal immunotherapeutic targets.

1749
01:40:25.340 --> 01:40:29.300
To address this question, we combined prostate cancer bone

1750
01:40:29.380 --> 01:40:33.360
biopsies with tumor-free bone samples and then performed further

1751
01:40:33.500 --> 01:40:34.720
single-cell analysis.

1752
01:40:35.520 --> 01:40:38.760
We identify multiple neutrophil subpopulations

1753
01:40:39.200 --> 01:40:41.640
corresponding to their developmental trajectories.

1754
01:40:42.480 --> 01:40:46.400
Notably, a mature neutrophil with elevated

1755
01:40:46.480 --> 01:40:49.740
expression of IL1B became

1756
01:40:49.840 --> 01:40:53.100
significantly enriched in tumor bone biopsies,

1757
01:40:53.700 --> 01:40:57.200
and we orthogonally confirmed their presence at protein levels

1758
01:40:57.560 --> 01:40:58.840
in bone biopsies.

1759
01:41:00.740 --> 01:41:04.580
Using a published gene signature of immune suppression, we found that

1760
01:41:04.640 --> 01:41:08.480
our target neutrophils show elevated immune-suppressive molecular

1761
01:41:08.500 --> 01:41:11.540
programs compared to other neutrophil subpopulations.

1762
01:41:13.000 --> 01:41:16.640
So we hypothesize that these IL1B mature

1763
01:41:16.700 --> 01:41:20.220
neutrophil may play a critical role in driving immunotherapy

1764
01:41:20.280 --> 01:41:23.040
resistance in prostate cancer bone metastasis.

1765
01:41:25.020 --> 01:41:28.580
To investigate in more detail, we utilize preclinical models.

1766
01:41:29.340 --> 01:41:32.560
We developed intraosseous prostate cancer model by

1767
01:41:32.640 --> 01:41:36.400
engrafting syngenic mouse prostate cancer directly into the

1768
01:41:36.460 --> 01:41:36.870
